把連登仔ff自己係純種白人嚟㗎<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"9952d50641860de99d30809f6ad9d606972085ab","tid":902464,"uid":23810,"like":1,"dislike":0,"score":1,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2018-11-28T06:52:12.000Z","msg":"我姓程 咁係咪去到外國點都會比人笑<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/frown.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"30d67950edfd4022ae1df008f11acc5306e13f56","tid":902464,"uid":171310,"like":7,"dislike":0,"score":7,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2018-11-28T06:56:36.000Z","msg":"其實Ching Chong 係笑緊早期俾人賣豬仔既人既廣東話"},{"pid":"fe86ff5200de9f5d268d4712f34a8a02a43fb6df","tid":902464,"uid":51933,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"quote":{"pid":"9d6ce615cdc4d1a6b0134dacf93f27afbfca4306","tid":902464,"uid":191366,"like":2,"dislike":1,"score":1,"quote":{"pid":"a8ce227bb113407dc9312166ff2a2ec4022e0bfc","tid":902464,"uid":51933,"like":0,"dislike":3,"score":-3,"citedBy":2,"replyTime":"2018-11-26T06:38:39.000Z","msg":"以前D鬼仔好多年前都已經係咁笑<br />\nching chong應該係似中國人講英文既發音"},"citedBy":2,"replyTime":"2018-11-28T06:38:34.000Z","msg":"其實係笑緊廣東話發音<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2018-11-28T14:53:38.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"/assets/faces/dog/give.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ching_chong\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FChing_chong&d=sIGfopfUIAdzml7A%2BFiBPjPUa9iY%2BpOmOVTB4fMSqaQ%3D&h=94e94f08\" target=\"_blank\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ching_chong</a><br />\n<br />\nThe term &quot;ching chong&quot; is based on how Chinese supposedly sounds to English speakers who do not speak it. <span style=\"color: red;\">The &quot;ch&quot; reflects the relative abundance of voiceless coronal affricates in Chinese (six in Mandarin Chinese: [ts], [tʂ], [tɕ], [tsʰ], [tʂʰ], [tɕʰ], respectively in Pinyin ⟨z⟩, ⟨zh⟩, ⟨j⟩, ⟨c⟩, ⟨ch⟩, and ⟨q⟩), whereas English only has two</span>: /tʃ/ (written ⟨ch⟩) and /ts/ (⟨ts⟩ or ⟨z⟩), of which only /tʃ/ regularly occurs initially. The &quot;ng&quot; reflects the greater commonness of nasals in syllable codas in many varieties of Chinese; for example, Mandarin only allows [n] or [ŋ] (written ⟨ng⟩ in both English and in romanization of Chinese) in syllable codas."},{"pid":"9743887aebb839fb2746790afaedcc203f6af215","tid":902464,"uid":16878,"like":1,"dislike":0,"score":1,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2018-11-28T23:03:07.000Z","msg":"<a href=\"https://youtu.be/HDHi8mE8RYE\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fyoutu.be%2FHDHi8mE8RYE&d=sIGfopfUIAdzml7A%2BFiBPjPUa9iY%2BpOmOVTB4fMSqaQ%3D&h=a46a88d6\" target=\"_blank\">https://youtu.be/HDHi8mE8RYE</a><br />\nIs it cool for me call you a Ching Chong rice eating motherfucker?"}]}